title: For Sale:  *Rare* IWI IDF-16 Tavor IDF Edition with Mepro 21 optic and BONUS accessories
location: Lake Worth, Palm Beach, South Florida
postcontent:
While Tavors may be common, this one is not- not by a longshot.
This is my IWI Tavor IDF-16, one of the rarer Tavors out there that not only features an integrated Mepro 21 Tritium/Fiber Optic dot sight (No Batteries Needed, Ever!), but also features more robust folding rear sights than the commercial SAR model (and Tritium, no less!). To my knowledge (unless something has changed), this rifle is unique in the sense that the barrel-mounted Mepro sight is the ONLY dot-reticled M21 currently supplied/mounted (via manufacturer) to any IDF model in the USA and is far superior to the triangle reticle these usually come with. You can remove the optic in exchange for a rail system.
This rifle has been kept in great condition for my personal rifle- the barrel and other components have been changed out for IWI factory parts. In short, it's more "Refurbished" than Used, to ensure you're nothing short of thrilled with it.
Unlike the traditional SAR model with the flimsy back up sights, these feature rotating/folding peep sights that perfectly co-witness with the optic, which is zeroed to 50/200 meters. With the right ammo and skill, I have taken out steel at 650 meters with this rifle. She's a piston gun and as robust at they come- she will likely outlive you and provide the defensive needs your family requires for generations to come.
She's compact. Shorter than many SBRs without the paperwork due to her bullpup design. I have been able to place her inside of small gym bags, pillowcases and backpacks. She is very well-balanced and loves to be fired from the standing and kneeling position (though the bench will do). You can fire her with one hand if you like, she doesn't mind and will gladly balance herself inside your shoulder. Recoil is mild and she's sure to turn some heads.
The IDF-16 variant of the Tavor is as close as you can get to the Israeli military-issued model and is devoid of all the fluff/quirks that many people dislike about the commercial US Tavor, including the newer X95s. She can take a serious beating and keep going, with or without cleaning and lubrication. She can be converted to 9mm with ease, and will come with a coveted barrel wrench in order for you to remove the barrel (cleaning is a breeze). That said, she isn't as cheap as the others- even used. She MSRPs at around $2,599, so this is a steal when you think about it. A new "bland" Tavor (without the IDF-16 features) sells around $1500, and a Mepro 21 MSRPs for about $550.
I chose the number 1812 due to Independence day, the Star Spangled Banner (written during the War of 1812) and even went down a few dollars of the appraised value to do so. Call me eccentric, I'm a patriotic kind of guy.
I loved this rifle. I still do. Why would I sell it, you ask? I'm getting married on July 4, so I have to make room for things. That said, I'm not desperate to offload her, so low-balling me will have zero effect. I may flex a little, but not much. It breaks my heart, but you gotta do what you gotta do.
I've used this rifle in competitions where I completely smoked AR users. Once you get the manual of arms down, she's as fast as lightning in terms of reloading, target acquisition and follow up shots. You can maneuver her in a way that would result in an AR being barrel-dragged through the mud. She's the perfect 5.56 home and vehicle defense rifle.
In addition to the carbine that served me so well, you will also get:
x1 Cyclone Plate Carrier, valued at $120, plus several pouches.
x1 Sling, Magpul.
x2 Magazines, Magpul, with 60 rounds of ammunition.
X1 Barrel wrench.
 
Priority will go to those with Concealed Carry Permits. Permit or no, a bill of sale will be signed, acknowledging that you are the purchaser of the firearm, legally allowed to own the rifle and do not plan to use it for illicit purposes.
Jump on this opportunity while you can. My loss will be your gain.

title: For Sale:  Franklin Armory BFS Binary Firing system trigger
postcontent: Description / Manufacturer Information: New Franklin Armory BFS Trigger. Franklin Armory's revolutionary Binary Firing System (BFS) is ideal for three gun competitors, tactical shooters, and recreational enthusiasts. It features a three position selector - Mode 1 for Safe, Mode 2 for traditional semi-automatic Mode, or Mode 3 for Binary Mode. In Binary Mode, the firearm will discharge one round with every function of the trigger, whether a pull or a release. A user can negate the round that would otherwise be fired during the release function by moving the selector back to Mode 2 and then safely releasing the trigger. Franklin Armory's BFS is easy to install with no custom fitting. The BFS Gen 3 offers a trigger pull of 4.5 lbs. (+/- 0.5 pound), the release phase now has a positive reset, and an updated design eliminates backup disconnector. The stronger buffer spring (included) reduces the possibility of hammer follow. It works in Franklin Armory's F17 series in .17 WSM without modification. It works on .22LR and 9mm uppers without modification. title: For Sale:  Colt M4 Expanse with PSA 16" Stainless Mid Length Upper and Eotech 512
postcontent: Hi All,Selling to thin the herd as I built this out of sheer boredom and have literally never put a single round through it.  This began life as a Colt M4 Expanse rifle.  I was not fond of the factory carbine length Colt upper as it did not come from Colt with a forward assist or dust cover.  Instead of adding those I elected to swap it out for a Palmetto State Armory upper featuring a 16" stainless barrel, mid length gas system, and Magpul MOE hand guards.  The BCG currently in the upper is also from PSA but the charging handle is a BCM Gunfighter Mod 4 (Medium).  From there I added a Matech BUIS and Eotech 512 holographic sight.  The grip was changed to a Magpul MIAD grip, and rear stock changed to a Magpul SL stock.  I have all the MIAD grip panels.  I have both original Colt grip and stock should you want them.  I also have the original Colt BCG should you want that instead of the PSA BCG.  The only thing I got rid of was the barreled Colt upper.  I DO NOT have the original Colt upper or barrel.  The rifle was $700 new, the Eotech was $429, the Magpul grip and stock was approx. $60 total, the Matech BUIS was $90.  The PSA complete upper was approx. $300 but I sold the Colt upper for about that so I suppose it cancels out in the end from a "dollars invested" perspective.  The rifle comes with 1 Magpul 30 round mag, and 1 original Colt 30 rd mag.  I have the original box and papers for the Eotech as well.  The Eotech is about 3 months old.

title: For Sale:  BARRETT 98B LIGHTWEIGHT 300WINMAG
postcontent: NO GAME TOO BIG. Carved from years of hard-earned insight, the Model 98B is entirely in a league of its own. This revolutionary precision rifle offers sub MOA long-range performance that others can only dream about. Its straight-line design allows for faster, more accurate follow-up shots that can tame the beast when hunting large game. Even the casual observer can see that the Model 98B is not a descendant of the bolt action sporting rifle. In fact, it's not a descendant of anything. Available in .338 Lapua Magnum, .300 Win Mag, .308 Win, .260 Rem, 6.5 Creed and 7mm Rem Mag, this rifle was developed to be a completely unique, purpose-built platform for precise long-range shooting. Its straight-line design, running from the highly efficient muzzle brake to the shooter's shoulder, tames recoil. It also allows for faster, more accurate follow-up shots fed from the 10-round detachable magazine. The ergonomic pistol grip reduces muscle fatigue and provides total control over the fully adjustable trigger. An intuitive, thumb-operated safety can be accessed without compromising the firing grip and allows the shooter to maintain a solid weld to the adjustable cheek piece. The oversized bolt handle can be easily manipulated, feeding a new round into the chamber as the bolt glides through a polymer guide. The Model 98B rifle's aluminum upper receiver boasts an M1913 optics rail, offering plenty of space to mount substantial optics as well as a night vision device or other accessories. The forward receiver is drilled and tapped for accessory rails to be mounted at the 3, 6 and 9 o'clock positions using KeyMod. From its shooter-adaptable design to its unprecedented performance, the 98B is ingenuity in action.
